To looking into the surface functional group and the chemical state of the WCDs and ECDs, XRD, XPS, and FTIR were performed. As shown in Fig. 3
                        A, the XRD spectrum shows WCDs and ECDs possess amorphous carbon and shows a characteristic diffraction peak at 20°, corresponding to the (002) face of graphite. The FTIR spectrum of WCDs reveals five peaks at 2924, 1676, 1556, 1199 and 1064 cm−1, which corresponds to the vibration absorbing of σCH2, amide I band, amide Ⅱ band, and stretching vibration of COC. The FTIR spectrum of ECDs displays four peaks at 2931, 1713, 1185 and 1041 cm−1, which corresponds to the vibration absorbing of σCH2, σCO, and stretching vibration of COC. WCDs exhibit obvious amide band vibration and ECDs demonstrate strong σCH2 and σCO vibration (Fig. 3B). The results indicated that different unsaturated double bond compounds could change the types and contents of the groups on the surface of CDs. FTIR of WCDs and ECDs with different concentrations of unsaturated double bond compounds were shown in Fig. S5. With the addition of AM, WCDs show significant absorption vibrations of σCH2, amide I band, amide II band and COC, as well as weaker OH vibrations (Fig. S5A). With the addition of AA, ECDs have significant absorption vibrations of σCH2, σCO, and COC, as well as weaker OH vibrations (Fig. S5B). WCDs showed significant amide band absorption, while the contents of σCH2 and σCO in ECDs were higher than those in WCDs with different concentrations of unsaturated double bond compounds. Furthermore, as shown in Fig. 3C and Fig. 3D, the three dominant peaks of 285, 401 and 532 eV in the XPS measurements belong to carbon/C1s, nitrogen/N1s, and oxygen/O1s elements in the WCDs and ECDs, respectively. The XPS spectra of N1s nuclear electrons show two fitting peaks at 399.7 (green) and 401.4 (blue) eV, which are related to the N in CNC and NH bond, respectively. Based on the integral area shown in Fig. 3Cii, their relative contents are 93% and 7% respectively. The XPS spectrum of C1s core electrons show three fitting peaks at 284.7 (green), 285.6 (blue) and 288.2 eV (yellow), which are linked to sp3-hybridized (CC), CO/CN and CO bonds. Their relative contents are 65%, 25%, and 10% respectively based on the integral area shown in Fig. 3Ciii. The high-resolution O1s spectrum can be fitted to two fitted peaks at 531.4 (green) and 532.4 (blue) eV, corresponding to CO and CO bonds (Fig. 3Civ). The relative contents are 48% and 52%. Furthermore, for ECDs, because of the low content of N elements, the peak of N1s is relatively messy (Fig. 3Dii). The C1s spectrum is deconvoluted into three peaks at 284.8 (green), 285.8 (blue) and 289.2 (yellow) eV, which are imputed to CC, CO/CN, and OCO bonds, respectively (Fig. 3Diii). The relative contents are 65%, 25%, and 10% respectively based on calculations of the integral area. The O1s spectrum reveals two peaks at 532.1 (green) and 533.4 eV (blue), which are affiliated to COC and OCO bonds, respectively (Fig. 3Div). The relative contents are 51% and 49%. As shown in Fig. S6, with the increase of AM content, the content of the N element in WCDs gradually increases, the content of CNC increases from 81% to 93%, and the content of NH decreases from 19% to 7%. The content of the N element in the structure (CNC) gradually increases, while the content of the surface (NH) decreases. This indicated that WCDs inherited amide bond from AM during the hydrothermal process. And for O1s, the content of CO increased from 25% to 48%, and the amount of CO dropped from 75% to 52%. Fig. S7 shows the XPS energy spectrum of ECDs when the content of AA is 0% and 20%. It is exhibited that the increase of acrylic acid content led to a significant decrease in the content of N and an increase in content of O in ECDs, resulting in the absence of hydrophilic amino groups on the surface. It could be seen from C1s and O1s that when the content of AA was 20%, the content of OCO in ECDs increased significantly, which corresponded to the strong σCO vibration at 1713 cm−1 in the FTIR spectrum. This indicated that ECDs obtained ester group formed between the carboxyl groups in AA and phenolic hydroxyl group in carrot, and the increase of OCO content led to the special solubility of ECDs during the hydrothermal process. The quantum yield of WCDs was determined as 3.4, 4.3, 5.3 and 5.8% respectively. And the quantum yield of ECDs was determined as 12.9, 15.2, 11.9, and 14.1% (Table 1
                        ). It’s observed that with the increased content of AM, the quantum yield of WCDs increased from 3.4% to 5.8%. The zeta potential of WCD is 32.27 eV, which has strong electronegativity. These results validated the consequence of XPS, and also explained the reasons why WCDs are pH dependent. On the other hand, the zeta potential of ECD is electrically neutral, which can be attributed to the ester group on its surface combined with XPS. The above results indicated that different precursors (AM and AA) will generate different kinds of CDs with different optical, phase and surface chemistry (Fig. 3E). Based on this free radical polymerization theory, by selecting different precursors reasonably, the target-oriented synthesis of the CDs could be successfully achieved.
